  "articleBody": "<!-- Page 8 --><article>\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Overview of the left inner shutter</h6>\n\n              <p>The action continues on the left inner shutter.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, view of the left inner shutter, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, view of the left inner shutter, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-40-img\" width=\"640\" height=\"1411\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/saint-jean_sans-cadre-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>the left inner shutter</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Scene of Salome's dance in Herod's palace, inside left shutter</h6>\n\n              <p>To succeed in making John die without causing any troubles among his supporters, <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">Herod imagined a staging</span>:</p>\n              <p>«on his birthday», he organized «a dinner for his dignitaries, for the chiefs of the army and for the notables of Galilee.</p>\n              <p>Herodiade <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salome\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salome\" id=\"salome\" class=\"yellow\">Salome</a>'s daughter» makes «her entrance» and dances.</p>\n              <p>The <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">\"Dance of Salome\"</span> takes place in a room in the tower of Herod's palace at the upper left of the left shutter, the wall of which Memling gutted to show the scene.</p>\n              <p>Above, statues set in niches represent a naked man between two naked women, pagan figures who allude to Herod's adulterous behaviour.</p>\n              <p>Overhead, statues set in niches depict a naked man between two naked women, pagan figures: they qualify the adulterous nature of the place and Herod's behavior.</p>\n\n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/salome-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Salome's Dance”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Salome's Dance”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-80-img\" width=\"640\" height=\"1252\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/salome-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>detail of the left inner shutter, “Salome's Dance”</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n                <p>Herod looks as if he liked his dance and, <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">to avoid responsibility for John's death, says</span> <span style=\"color: #999;\">(Mark, chapter 6, verses 22 to 25)</span>:</p>\n\n                <blockquote cite=\"https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Bible_(World_English)/Mark#6:22\">\n                  <ol class=\"doc\">\n                    <li value=\"22\">\n                      <p class=\"conversation\">\n                        «“<span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">Ask me whatever you want</span>, and I will give it to you”.\n                      </p>\n                    </li>\n                    <li value=\"23\">\n                      <p>He swore to her,</p>\n                      <p class=\"conversation\">\n                        “Whatever you shall ask of me, I will give you, up to half of my kingdom.”\n                      </p>\n                    </li>\n                    <li value=\"24\">\n                      <p>Salome went out, and said to her mother,</p>\n                      <p class=\"conversation\">\n                        <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">“What shall I ask?”</span>»\n                      </p>\n                      <p>Herodias said,</p>\n                      <p class=\"conversation\">\n                        «<span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">“The head of John, the one who baptises”</span>.\n                      </p>\n                    </li>\n                    <li value=\"25\">\n                      <p>She came in immediately with haste to the king, and asked,</p>\n                      <p class=\"conversation\">\n                        <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">“I want you to give me right now the head of John the one who baptises on a platter.”</span>.\n                      </p>\n                    </li>\n                  </ol>\n                </blockquote>\n\n                <p>Thus Herod can appear to put John to death against his will.</p>\n                <p>The proof that this whole story is indeed a smokescreen designed to allow John to be put to death without provoking a revolt by John's supporters is, as Jacobus da Varagine explains, that if Salome asks Herod <span style=\"color: #e6a64d;\">«the death of her father <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_II\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_II\" id=\"herode-boethos-2\" class=\"yellow\">Philip</a> or her mother <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herodias\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herodias\" id=\"herodiade-2\" class=\"yellow\">Herodias</a>»</span>, Herod cannot consent to it <span style=\"color: #999;\">(<cite>The Golden Legend</cite> chapter 121, paragraph I. <a id=\"renvoi-note-8\" href=\"#note-8\"><sup>note 8</sup></a> )</span>.</p>\n                <p>The only purpose of the smokescreen is indeed to avoid placing the responsibility for John's killing on Herod by falsely presenting him in the eyes of history as acceding to this request against his will.</p>\n\n\n\n\n            <h6 class=\"yellow\">Scene of the beheading of John in the courtyard of Herod's palace, from the inner left shutter</h6>\n\n              <p>So history is accomplishing itself, tragically.</p>\n              <p>A guard is going to «behead John in the prison» <span style=\"color: #999;\">(Mark, chapter 6, verse 28)</span>.</p>\n            \n            <figure>\n              <picture><source sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-280.webp 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-380.webp 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-480.webp 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-640.webp 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-840.webp 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1280.webp 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1600.webp 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1920.webp 1920w\" type=\"image/webp\"><img src=\"/docs/saint-jean/decollation-640.jpg\" title=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" alt=\"Hans MEMLING, “Triptych of John the Baptist and John the Evangelist”, detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”, Memling Museum, Old St. John's Hospital, Bruges (Brugge)\" class=\"class-diane-img\" width=\"640\" height=\"991\" sizes=\"(max-width: 767px) 98vw, (min-width: 959px) 50vw, 86vw\" srcset=\"\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-280.jpg 280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-380.jpg 380w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-480.jpg 480w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-640.jpg 640w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-840.jpg 840w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1280.jpg 1280w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1600.jpg 1600w,\n              /docs/saint-jean/decollation-1920.jpg 1920w\"></picture><figcaption>detail of the left inner shutter, “Decollation of John the Baptist”</figcaption>\n            </figure>\n\n\n</article>"
